	Confidentiality, Integrity, Authentication
	- cyptographic primitives

	six design priniciples for military ciphers:
		The system must be practically, if not mathematically indecipherable
		It muust not be required to be a secret, and it must be able to fall into the hands of the enemy without inconvenience
			secret system makes untestable system - defender mindset
		Key must be communicable and retainbale without the help of written notes and changeable or midifiable at the will of the correspondents
		it must be applicable to telegraphic correspondents
		Apparatus and documents must be portable, and its usage and function must not require the concourse of several peopole.
		the system must be easy to use, requiring neither mental strain nor the knowledge of a long seies of rules to observe.

security through obscurity is bad

